---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { sourceUrl } from '../lib/sessions';
import { site } from '../site';

const src = (path: string) =>
  sourceUrl(site.designSystemRepoUrl, site.designSystemDefaultBranch, path);
---

<Base title="Models — Field Notes from Selvedge" activeNav="models">
  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="meta">Models</div>
    <h1>What we've noticed about models.</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A living record of what this project has learned about how AI models behave. Updated every few sessions, not every one.</p>
  </header>

  <p>
    This page collects things we have learned about how models behave from running this
    project. We use <strong>model</strong> throughout for what is sometimes called an AI,
    an LLM, or a foundation model. <em>Claude family</em> and <em>non-Claude</em> refer
    to the specific models the project has used in deliberation — we do not claim these
    observations generalise to models we have not tried.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sessions referenced below are recorded in the project's main repository. The
    links point to specific files there so a curious reader can read the source
    material directly.
  </p>

  <h2>Same-family models share a framing, not just an answer</h2>

  <p>
    When you ask several instances of the same model family to take different sides of
    a question, they produce different answers, but inside the same framing. The
    disagreements stay within a shape none of them can see, because the shape is part
    of what their training has in common. Bringing in a model from a different lineage
    changes this. The non-Claude model does not only give a different answer; it often
    sees that the question was being asked in a particular shape at all, and reframing
    the question is frequently what gets the group unstuck.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen in
      <a href={src('provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md')}>Session 009</a>
      and
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md')}>Session 012</a>,
      in the non-Claude model's responses.
    </em>
  </p>

  <h2>A model can see patterns in another model that the second cannot see in itself</h2>

  <p>
    In one case, a non-Claude model was asked to predict what a group of Claude-family
    models would do before seeing their work. It predicted they would reach for names
    built out of their current working vocabulary rather than from outside it. The
    Claude-family models then produced exactly that, independently, without knowing the
    prediction had been made. A model from one lineage could anticipate another
    lineage's tendencies from the outside in a way the second lineage could not see
    in itself.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen in Session 012, comparing the
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md')}>non-Claude model's prediction</a>
      against
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/01a-perspective-namer.md')}>the Claude-family response that matched it</a>.
    </em>
  </p>

  <h2>Words from the input leak into the output</h2>

  <p>
    When a model is given a briefing to reason from, vocabulary from the briefing tends
    to show up in its response even when the model is supposed to be producing original
    thinking. This makes it hard to tell whether the model reasoned independently or
    just re-used the language it was given. The practical fix is to write briefings
    that do not pre-load the terms you want to test. The honest test of independent
    thinking is whether the response contains language that was not in the input.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen across sessions; the most recent audit is in
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/03-close.md')}>Session 012's close note</a>,
      where the novel terms produced by each model are listed.
    </em>
  </p>
</Base>
